It is crucial to recognize the importance of reducing greenhouse gas emissions, but it is equally important to address the geopolitical implications of supporting a country with a track record of human rights abuses and aggressive behavior.
By weaponizing the "Green Deal" and urging individuals to transition away from gasoline-powered vehicles, President Biden is taking important steps towards combatting climate change and reducing greenhouse gas emissions. However, concerns have been raised regarding the financial support provided to China, the world's biggest polluter.
The fact that Biden is providing financial support to China through the "Green Deal" while China prepares for war raises questions about the effectiveness and ethical implications of such policies. Supporting a country that contributes significantly to global pollution and has a dubious track record on human rights sends a conflicting message about the priorities and policies of the United States.
However, as China silently prepares for war, it is important for the international community to closely monitor their actions and intentions. The preparation for war, if true, raises significant concerns about regional and global stability. Transparency and open dialogue between nations become even more crucial in navigating through these complex circumstances.
While combining climate change initiatives with political maneuvering Joe Biden sold out America for cheap by using "the green deal" attempting to force all Western countries to stop Oil/Gas production by blending their weapon as the "Cure" in an attempt to finance China directly. 
As China silently prepares for war by sending spy balloons all over the US and awaiting the end of Western GAS due to Joe Biden's policies by weaponizing Russia sanctions not only against Russia but against their own allies UK/EU, Joe Biden set the record straight and destroyed the Nord Stream pipeline.
It is imperative that the Biden administration reevaluates its approach, considering the potential security implications of its environmental policy initiatives. While the focus on climate change and the transition to renewable energy should remain a priority, it is crucial to ensure that our actions do not inadvertently strengthen a potential adversary.
In conclusion, the concerns raised regarding financial support to China alongside its alleged silent war preparations are significant. China's quest for dominance in the global arena, coupled with its disregard for environmental standards, raises serious questions about the wisdom of providing financial support to a country that is already responsible for a significant portion of the world's pollution. By doing so, we may inadvertently be fueling China's ability to further its military ambitions, posing a threat to regional stability and potentially even global security.

As an EV owner, this video was poorly researched and only promoted fear of the transition.  An American can now purchase a Chevrolet Bolt for less than $30,000, before the $7,500 federal tax rebate, plus more at the state level in many states.  The grid is being updated, and thousands of new charging stations are being installed, as well as Tesla opening up their chargers to non-Tesla autos.   In the meantime, petroleum is killing the planet, the direct cause of all the crazy weather, all over the globe that is now affecting our food supply.  This change can't happen fast enough, and this story is laden with half truths, and no factual information about how much owning an EV costs LESS than owning an Internal Combustion Engine (ICE) vehicle.  Start running THOSE stories instead of this BS that was probably done to appease the fossil fuel business.

HERE'S SOME ANSWERS.  An apartment dweller who parks your car off the street can probably charge with a heavy extension cord plugged into the outside plug, or inside.  Or, you can go to a Fast Charge station and do most of your charging, abuot 180 miles worth no more than an hour.  Fast chargers are now located at most Walmarts and Sam's clubs, and all over most urban/suburban areas.  check the website www.plugshare.com for locations, or get the app for your mobile phone.  A Chevy Bolt will fast charge in 45 minutes to an hour, giving 180 miles of range for less than $10.  Can you drive your current auto that far, that cheap?  If you get a level two charger installed in your garage or on the side of your house, you can fully charge your car overnight while you sleep for around $3. (YES, THREE DOLLARS) worth of electricity.  Can you drive your current car over 200 miles for THREE DOLLARS?  
A Chevy Bolt is around $22,000 aafter the federal tax rebate, and some states also offer rebates.

Surely a simple annual road tax would be by far the easiest duty to administer and police? Every car would accrue a single road tax each year. Vehicle types could be grouped in one of a handful of categories and tax rates, just as happens in the U.K. and in a number of other countries. The figures involved would be standardised and easy to administer either online, via post offices or by post. Any vehicle which is due to be taxed would be put onto a state or national database, and any owner who has not taxed their vehicle(s) would be flagged immediately by the database. A SORN system (Statutory Off Road Notification) option would allow for people who are either scrapping their vehicle or only going to be using it on private land. Those vehicles would also be flagged if they are seen being used on public roads. Reasonably easy to police in this computerised world, and very efficient, if done properly.

The repealed tax was, or would have been, a nightmare for government employees to calculate, check, bill and collect. Can you imagine the mayhem which would be caused in trying to ensure that each driver of each of their vehicles kept accurate records of every journey throughout each year, and then submitted them on time and with no errors? Then who would have to be paid to handle the ensuing queries and disputes? And who would have to be paid to police it?

The whole thing would be incredibly inefficient and chaotic, especially if many people objected to the tax, as they clearly did. And even if they didn't object, then how many of us have imperfect memories, and make mistakes and omissions? I know of nobody who is absolutely perfect! Let's face it, many people have little idea about how much money they spend in each retail outlet each week, and few keep scrupulously accurate records of even simple and regular expenses. Many others only have a vague idea about how much money is in their regular salary or about how much tax is being stopped from the gross amount.

To be clear this is a technical taxation ruling and nothing more:

The high court has correctly held that no State or Territory can apply a tax, levy, duty or fee that only impacts one sub product within a taxable group differently to the other products within that group for example NSW's fee structure for registration is weight based that's perfectly OK because it taxes all cars equally based on a metric not a specific product - any State or Local government can use general metrics like weight, size, $value etc to determine taxation rates - they can't however single out a product within that group to apply different rules to, or apply a tax, duty, levy, fee etc. to only that sub-type of product within that group, that type of product or sub product specific tax can only be levied by the Federal government and must apply equally to all places in Australia.

It leaves the door open for a Federal tax on a per kilometre usage basis that can be redistributed back to the States.

The US State of Washington experimented with various ways of funding road maintenance  and construction several years ago.  One of the alternatives was taxation by mile rather than volume of fuel purchased in the state.  A recording device that could *not* be used to track the vehicle was installed that recorded mileage on each type of public road, whether maintained by city, county or state, and automatically delivered the road use tax (calculated to replace fuel tax revenues) to the appropriate agencies.  During the test phase, those who chose that method got refunds for the fuel taxes they paid.  (Not sure just how they figured that out, but they did.)  It was very popular among those who chose it.  It was well received by the government agencies because they received the monies steadily rather than having to negotiate a yearly lump sum payment with the state (which collected the fuel taxes).  That is certainly fair.

A few corrections. 

Those who failed to comply had the vehicle registration cancelled, not the drivers licence.

In order to comply, a photo of the odometer was required. It may have been that a log book could be used, but this was overkill and not essential. After all, why would the government care when and where you drove if all that mattered was how many kilometres you drove in the year?

Road funding is supplied by all three levels of government. Local councils are responsible for basically the suburban or town streets. The state government is responsible for major roads with the federal government chipping in for some major projects. I'd hate anyone to walk away thinking that the Victorian government was taxing people to pay for road funding they didn't do. Also, the federal fuel excise goes into general revenue and the funding it provides for roads is drawn from that source. It's not as if the fuel excise goes 100% into roads and when the fuel money runs out, funding runs out. It doesn't work like that.

The EV tax, while being the tax that instigated the High Court case, was not the only tax that is impacted. At the time of federation, the states ceded a number of taxation types to the federal government. Relevant to this case were taxes related to the production, manufacture, sale, distribution, or consumption of goods. This was a tax on the 'consumption' of the roads. Those from the US may find it unusual that we have no state sales tax. This is why.

As Sam said, Victoria was the first state to go down this path but others were certain to follow. My guess is that the decision will also block state congestion taxes, another idea that has been floated over the years.

Finally, I think we can do without the political commentaries. Yes, getting rid of this tax was a good thing. Yes, there will need to be some restructuring of taxes in general to cover road funding. Yes, the loss of the fuel excise will leave a hole in federal finances. As for the rest of the political commentary, it is best left out of the videos as much of it is dubious to say the least.

The EV tax was a joke considering it's a federal government excise as mentioned but I don't why why Sam is trying to make out the tax to be so complicated in terms of keeping logbook every time you drive and where you drove etc. It's just a photo of the odometer either when you buy an EV, when you renew your registration, or when you sell. No difficult and time consuming tasks and I'm fairly sure it was only a small number of people that had their registrations cancelled indefinitely for not complying.

Within the next 10 years there will almost certainly be an EV charge that will be distance based that will be administered by the federal government as; EV uptake surpasses 50% of new vehicles, the need for incentives is minimal, and the need to replace the fuel excise increases.

I'll explain.  First, finances and economy.  In the United States, the average income in the U.S. is $37,000, which is only up $3,000 from 12 years ago.  The Median income is about $57,000.  Let's differentiate here because it's important.  This is a great definition of the difference between the two:  "The average is calculated by adding up all of the individual values and dividing this total by the number of observations. The median is calculated by taking the “middle” value, the value for which half of the observations are larger and half are smaller."  
But, the average cost of a vehicle has gone insane, as with food, housing, and all the other costs of living.  In January 2012, the average cost of an automobile was $30,570, in March of 2023 it was almost $49,000, or over a 60% increase in price.  It is not really possible for most people to purchase a new car today, and really, to purchase a new car, finance it for so many years, and still have enough money to meet other needs, i.e., housing, food, medical, and retirement, you need to be making about $200,000 a year.  This is starting to sink in.  When you go into a dealership and you have to put down $8,000 as the downpayment on a new car, and if you have really good credit, you might get a car loan as low as 6.34%.
So, let's say I want to buy a new Toyota Crown, let's say I got a good deal, and it's going to cost me $45,000.  I have a 60-month loan at 6.34%.  I am able to put down $9,000, in either cash or trade.  I live in a West Coast blue state that has a tax of 10%.  My loan amount is $36,500, my sales tax is $4,550 and my upfront payment is $14,550.  The Interest on the loan is $6,186, and my loan payments over 60 months are $42,685 for a total cost of $57,236.  That works out to a car payment of $711.43 per month.  In your first year, you will pay $6,407 in principal and $2,130 in interest.
Most people today can not afford that.  Also, used car prices are insane, but your trade-in value has not substantially increased.

So many years ago, when I was in school, we were taught that our housing costs, including rent and utilities or mortgage and utilities, should not be more than 25% of our income.  Back around 2010, and even before, that number was raised to 33%.  Today, people are paying in excess of 50% of their income for housing.  Even if you make the Median Income of $57,000, that only gives you $1,100 per week.  Given the rule of thumb I was taught in school, your mortgage or rent, including utilities, shouldn't be more than $1,100 or so per month.  As an example, I said I live on the West Coast.  In 2008, I purchased a 2 bed, 1.75 bath, 1,000sf condo for $137,500.  Today, a condo in that same complex is pending sale for $315,000!  My mortgage payment with a no-money down VA loan was less than $800 a month, plus a $500 HOA fee.  With a 20% down payment ($63,000) that condo would cost $2,320 per month plus the $500 or so per month Condo fee.  That's $33,840 per year with a mortgage rate of 8.219% for a 30-year mortgage.   For that 25% rule of thumb, you'd need to be making about $136,000 per year, or $101,500 if you use 33%.  This is a two-bedroom condo!  Imagine adding $8,500 to that to pay for your car.  That's $44,000+ per year just for a two-bedroom condo and your car.

How many people, really, have the ability to make that kind of payment.  Okay, I don't live in those condos any more, but the one I lived in had 12 units in my building, and some of the other buildings had 18 units per building.  They all were set back from the parking lot and we didn't have any garages.  So, now, you're going to have to charge your car.  That means installing a charging station.  Each one of the units had one assigned parking spot.  You would need to install a charging station for each unit, whether or not they had an EV, because you didn't know if they were going to buy one or not.  It would be difficult, if not downright impossible to feasibly install the power for the charging station to go to each unit, at least with any fiscal responsibility.  That means that the condo association would probably have to provide the power to the charges, and you could be paying a monthly fee for the electricity that you used to the Homeowner's Association.  The fiscal hurt of that would have to be absorbed by the owners, regardless of whether they had an EV or not.  How much would that add to your HOA fee (remember, this one is already at $500 per month).
If you have a home of your own, then you'd just pay an electrician a couple of thousand dollars to come out and install your $500 charging station.

While EV sales are strong, right now, they are slacking off.  Prices continue to rise, moving them out of the reach of the people they need to be selling to the most.  The price IS falling, the average cost of an EV in the U.S. is only about $54,000, down from a year ago.  But, then again, the average cost of an ICE car is $48,000.  So, really not too much of a difference.

Then there is the reliablity.  Tesla is probably the largest EV car manufacturer in the world, and how many of their cars, for no apparent reason, just have a battery fault and burst into flames?  Ooops, my $54,000 car just burned up.  There are some insurance companies now refusing to insure EVs.  If an EV gets into an accident, it often is considered 'totaled' even though comparable damage on an ICE vehicle would be repaired and paid for, the chief reason being the cost of the battery.  Any minor damage to the battery risks a short, fire or other damage resulting in the loss of the car.  So, if the battery is damaged at all, the entire cost of the automobile is written off.  Hence, the cost of insuring an EV is more.

The battery warranty is for 1,50,000 km in ev, so let's our goal is 1.5L km.

For petrol, milage: 17km, price: 97/-
So running cost = 1,50,000/17×97 = 8,55,882/- ( on current fuel price ) 
Maintenance cost at per 10k km = 4,000/- ( min )
So for 1.5L km = 4,000×15 = 60,000/-

Total = 8,55,882 + 60,000 = 9,15,882/- ( min )

For EV, milage: 300km, price for 1 unit : 7/- ( min )
Running cost for 1.5L km = 1,50,000÷300×40×7 = 1,40,000/- 
Maintenance cost = 60,000 ( max ) 

Total = 1,40,000 + 60,000 = 2,00,000/-

So which is a better choice 🤔

Lithium hydroxide can be recycled from various sources, including lithium-ion batteries, by following certain processes:

1. **Battery Recycling**: Lithium hydroxide can be recycled from lithium-ion batteries by disassembling the batteries and extracting the lithium-containing components. These components are then subjected to processes such as leaching, precipitation, and filtering to separate and recover lithium compounds.

2. **Chemical Processes**: The recovered lithium hydroxide can undergo chemical processes to purify and regenerate the compound. This might involve dissolving the compound in water, then using chemical reactions to separate impurities and regenerate the pure lithium hydroxide.

3. **Electrochemical Methods**: Electrochemical processes can also be used to recycle lithium compounds. In some cases, lithium hydroxide can be electrochemically converted back into lithium metal, which can then be used to produce new lithium-ion batteries.

4. **Ion Exchange**: Ion exchange resins or membranes can be used to selectively extract and recover lithium ions from solutions containing lithium hydroxide. This method can be particularly useful for recycling lithium from industrial processes.

5. **Hydrometallurgical Techniques**: These techniques involve using various chemicals and processes to selectively dissolve lithium compounds, separate them from other materials, and then recover and purify the lithium hydroxide.

Recycling lithium hydroxide and other lithium compounds is important for reducing the environmental impact of lithium-ion batteries and conserving valuable resources. As the demand for lithium-ion batteries continues to grow, improving recycling methods will become increasingly essential.

Feb。25， 2023， CHINA： The first domestic A00-class test vehicle powered by sodium-ion batteries was unveiled, and its appearance represents a new breakthrough in China's electric vehicles.

New energy electric vehicles have three cores: power battery, electric drive and electric control. Among them, the mainstream of power battery is still lithium battery. Using sodium-ion batteries as power batteries is tantamount to changing the "heart" of electric vehicles, and the performance, quality and reliability of the entire vehicle will be affected.

However, the performance of this "new heart" is really impressive. The data shows that the battery capacity of the first sodium battery car in China is 25kWh, and the cruising range is 250km, which has a certain gap with the lithium electric car, but it is not a big problem to meet the urban commuting. And in terms of fast charging, sodium batteries only need 15-20 minutes to charge once, which is much better than lithium batteries!

 The sodium-ion batteries can cut the cost of battery by 30%.

From Business Insider (Yahoo) excerpts: The 2023 Toyota bZ4X AWD Limited. Tim Levin/Insider
Let's nerd out for just one moment to establish some basic concepts.
Every EV has a maximum charging rate, expressed in kilowatts (kW), that governs the amount of power it can accept from roadside fast chargers. For the bZ4X AWD Toyota provided, that's an uncompetitive 100 kW. The higher an EV's rating, the faster you can hypothetically charge  — so long as you find a charging plug whose rating is equal or greater.
But you don't always achieve that max charge rate due to the charger, the temperature of the battery, or, in my case, settings built into the vehicle itself. During my trip, the car never got close to 100 kW, leading to some excruciating charging times. The 2023 Toyota bZ4X AWD Limited. Tim Levin/Insider
 I drove the new Toyota bZ4X electric SUV from New York to Washington DC, and back. The nine-hour drive involved three hours of charging.

EVs have traditionally had higher upfront costs, with the price of the battery a chief factor. But the average price for batteries fell to  $98.20 per kilowatt-hour last month, according to energy analytics firm Benchmark Mineral Intelligence, the first time in two years it has dipped below $100. 

Battery pack prices need to reach $100 per kilowatt-hour for EVs to achieve price parity with their fossil-fuel counterparts, Benchmark said.
"Decreasing cell prices could allow [original equipment manufacturers] to sell mass-market EVs at comparable prices to ICE vehicles, with the same margin, improving the attractiveness of the EV transition for both consumers and automakers," Benchmark analyst Evan Hartley said in a statement.

A decade ago, lithium-ion batteries averaged $668 per kilowatt-hour. By March 2022, they were down to $146.40, falling another 33% to reach August's average. According to market intelligence firm TrendForce, "a continued gradual price decline [should be] expected for the rest of the year."

It is true that in terms of the offer of electric cars, the Chinese automotive industry crushes the European one. I don't look at the European automotive industry, but rather at the domestic one, because I live in Poland. The truth is that we never played a significant role in the world of combustion motoring, and ours died with FSO and was full of archaic structures. First things first. After the war, the government decided to rebuild the Polish automotive industry, which dates back to 1918. The key problem for the government was the license to produce a car. Due to the pre-war cooperation of the Polish automotive industry with Fiat, they were talking to Fiat about the license production of the 1100 model, a small, relatively accessible family car. Unfortunately, in 1949, the contract was terminated for political reasons and in 1951, the FSO Warszawa, a licensed version of the Gaza M-20 Pobeda, went into production. The problem is that in the 1950s it was positioned much higher and was intended for politicians, state services and wealthy customers, and the FSC Żuk and ZSD Nysa, based on Soviet mechanics, were delivery vehicles. And society needed something economic. This is how the FSO/FSM Syrena was created, the only fully Polish design that was not without flaws, and it was in 1957. The only relatively recognizable brand was Polski Fiat, reactivated in the 1960s, but under which we promoted Italian technology and Italian cars. The Polish Fiat 125p, which debuted in 1967, was technically based on its predecessor, the 1300/1500, and was modernized many times. First, in 1973, the interim MR73 series appeared, followed by the MR75 series in 1975, produced until 1982. The result of such a policy of mindless pursuit of foreign exchange was an economic crisis that lasted throughout the 1980s and it was necessary to look for savings wherever possible. And since the license expired, in 1983 this angular sedan was called FSO 1500 and in the 1980s it was a much cheaper alternative to its much more expensive successor, FSO Polonez. Fiat 128 3p, Fiat 128 Sport and Fiat 132p were assembled at FSO. The Fiat 126p produced at FSM was an exact license of the original, and definitely the most successful one, because not only was it the cheapest and it brought motorization to the country, it also consumed little fuel and drove like a go-kart. The previously mentioned FSO Polonez, which was also an Italian project bought by FSO and previously rejected by Lancia, was more prestigious than its predecessor, the Fiat 125p, which was a cheaper alternative. The truth is that apart from the FSO/FSM Syrena, which was the only fully Polish car, the rest were either licensed versions or based on the floor plate and mechanics of either the Gaza M20 Pobieda or the Fiat 1300/1500 produced in the 1960s. The FSR Tarpan, a car primarily for farmers, and prototypes such as the Polski Fiat 125p Coupe, FSO 1300 Coupe, and FSO Ogar were also based on their technology. As FSM throughout its history only had its logo on the Syrena 105 taken over from FSO and its Bosto and R20 variants produced in 1971-1983, and had been producing the Polish Fiat 126p since 1973, in 1992 they were bought by Fiat and renamed them to Fiat. Auto Poland. Although the factory continues to operate, FSM itself has been closed. In 1994, the Polski Fiat brand made history. Volkswagen took over FSR, and after the Poznań factory went bankrupt, it was renamed Volkswagen Poznań. Meanwhile, at FSO, trade unions were demanding and ultimately the Korean concern Daewoo became the owner, which resulted in maintaining employment, modernizing the obsolete FSO Polonez, resulting in the Caro Plus series and producing cars such as Tico, Lanos, Matiz, Leganza, Nubira and Tacuma, which They were extremely popular in Poland. Unfortunately, the Daewoo concern itself was not reliable and went bankrupt in 2001, taking with it many manufacturers it owned, including FSO. Then Daewoo was bought by General Motors, which also had no idea for FSO apart from the licensed production of the Chevrolet Aveo, first in a sedan version, and then in a 3- and 5-door version. And here we come to 2009, when General Motors went bankrupt and the American government ordered them to purge them, so over the following years Opel, Vauxhall and Saab were sold (it went bankrupt in 2012), Pontiac, Saturn, Hummer, Daewoo and Holden were closed. , and in February 2011, production of the Chevrolet Aveo ended, and thus FSO went bankrupt and was one of the victims of the purge at General Motors. It is true that there was an intensive search for an investor, but nothing came of it. Currently, the only heir to FSO may be Izera, a manufacturer of electric cars, provided that the factory is built and everything goes according to plan. However, unlike western countries with huge automotive achievements, we have nothing to lose, because we do not have any automotive brand of our own, our internal combustion cars were very outdated compared to
Western competition, and our economy is far behind even those from the so-called old EU countries.  Only modernizations were Polish.  So we can ask ourselves what's the harm if we don't have our own car brand anyway, then in our Polish case, electrification and cooperation with China is an opportunity to draw conclusions from the past, bounce back from the economic bottom where we are now and avoid a number of mistakes made  by, among others, the no longer existing FSO.

In the early 2000s, before it fully ventured into the field of EVs, China’s car industry was in an awkward position. 
China decided to break away from the established technology and invest in completely new territory: cars powered entirely by batteries. 
For China, EVs also had the potential to solve several other major problems, like curbing its severe air pollution, reducing its reliance on imported oil, and helping to rebuild the economy after the 2008 financial crisis. 
It seemed like a win-win for China.
China took steps to invest in related technologies as early as 2001.
EV technology was introduced as a priority science research project in China’s Five-Year Plan, the country’s highest-level economic blueprint. 
Since then, EV development has been consistently prioritized in China’s national economic planning. 
About one-quarter of passenger cars sold in China last year were all-electric or plug-in hybrid vehicles, compared with about 7% in the US.
China is way ahead of the US in terms of EV adoption.
China has implemented supportive policies to bolster the growth of the EV industry. 
In line with the dual-carbon target, China introduced the “New Energy Vehicle Industry Development Plan (2021-2035)” on November 2, 2020.
China is by far the global leader in making EV batteries.
China is far ahead of the rest of the world in the development of batteries that use sodium, which are starting to compete with ubiquitous lithium power cells.
Today, fierce competition in China has spurred rapid development of the EV industry. 
China is both the largest auto and electric vehicle market in the world and home to an estimated 200 EV manufacturers. 
Faced with pressure and competition at home, China’s EV makers are pursuing expansion abroad, especially in emerging markets. 
Last year, China’s exports of EVs increased 131.8% year on year to around 680,000 units, official data showed. 
Thanks in part to the surge in EV sales, China overtook Japan as the world’s top auto exporter in the first quarter of this year.

In regards to the car makers adapting to climate change. 

80% of Minis are exported overseas. 109 countries purchase minis built in Oxford UK. 

In 2021 mini had its highest year in domestic sales, 46'000 new vehicles sold in the UK. That is against a background of currently 30 million passenger cars in the UK from all makers and 1 million new vehicles purchased per year. 

So minis domestic marketplace is small. 

The point here no one is emphasising is this. 

These UK based car manufacturers are not doing this green initiative to clean up Britain as the majority of sales are exported overseas.  
 
The manufacturers are doing it to meet carbon limits during manufacture so they avoid climate tarrifs but exporting greener vehicles overseas does nothing to lower vehicle emissions output within the UK by these domestic manufacturers. 

Exporting vehicles still requires large freight supersize container ships that burn diesel fuel. 

EV batteries still require highly toxic rare earth minerals and metals sourced in third world regions often mined by slave labour, underage labour in terrible working conditions. 
Regions such as war torn DRC in central Africa. 

The domestically sourced lithium is not enough to provide enough EV batteries to keep pace with UK vehicle production. 

A large part of the green initiative was to source and use locally.

Therefore this exercise falls short of being an adequate solution to tackling climate change. 

Its closer to big corporations avoiding business carbon tariffs by using tax payer subsides/government loans.

Very good video. While brief, it dived deeply into aspects that many 'Why China is so good at EV' articles/videos didn't. For instance, it is rarely mentioned that China's EV development can be dated back to early 2000s, not 2010s. 2010s was, at the video correctly identified, where this development is on the next gear, rather than its origin.

Still, a few points I'd like to add.

1. The development got its ups and downs. It's not just 'throw some money year after year and it's done'. There are setbacks. There are adjustments. The subsidy fraud thing was actually  quite serious then. There were others as well, like how to determine to best form of subsidy - it it consumer? Some form of quotas? Should it focus on big, advanced luxurious cars? Or should it be general? This is actually quite a journey and show the smart adaptation of the Chinese government

2. Speaking of the fierce internal competition, Tesla occupies an important role here. Tesla has been considered the best brand in China for a long time. So, in order to cut a share in the market, Chinese EV companies ha木 to directly compete against Tesla. This spurs great product development. They tried to chase Tesla in certain performance metrics, while developing new edges (like software integration, which is very very good). They also dominate the lower-end markets which is more price-sensitive. I think right now, Tesla is still considered the best, but BYD is a very close second. and 5 years ago this would sound ridiculous. That's what the competition has done.

3. The help on EV is far beyond just consumer subsidy. One thing: infrastructural buildup like charging stations, laws and regulation, suppression of ICE vehicles etc. China is basically leaps and bounds ahead of all countries, even European ones, in this regard. The infrastructural buildups is especially important - Imagine cutting 90% of gas station and see how it affects the ICE car market.

4. There's an underlying strategic logic behind China's massive and sustained investment in EV. The basic idea is that newcomers are hard to challenge established ones in existing market. The only way for China to get ahead of the technologically advanced west is to get into new products like EVs. That way, all countries have the same starting point, and in this case with smart policies and subsidies + a huge internal market, China could be very successful - and it did. This sort of thinking can date back even before 2000s - and in the early 2000s China decided to experiment and test out different fields and see which one is worth further developing - and EV is one of them, and the rest is history.

The EVs will be a passing phase in personal transport as they have too many disadvantages.
The flammability of the lithium battery, the need for relatively long charging time even for fast charging, the scarcity of charging stations at suitable locations, the safe disposal of depleted battery are just some of the problems of EVs.
The future fuel is likely to be hydrogen or a safer form of it in a host chemical such as an ammonia compound.
Much R&D are being carried out on these hydrogen fueled vehicles at the moment and China should put some resources on this research.
Ultimately green energy from renewables such as solar or wind (even nuclear reactors) will provide the electricity to power the world. Electricity will generate the hydrogen from water via hydrolysis.
The combustion products of hydrogen in air is pure water and is non polluting.
A real advantage.

I am not against progress, new technologies should come, and so should new vehicles but no govt can forcibly take away peoples' vehicles which are 100% fit and well maintained. It's tyranny.

BYD is a Chinese electric car company that has been successful in selling electric vehicles (EVs) in several countries, including China and Europe. However, it has faced challenges when it comes to selling its EVs in the United States.

One reason for this is that the US market is highly competitive, and there are already many established players in the EV space, such as Tesla, General Motors, and Ford. These companies have large marketing budgets and established sales channels, which can make it difficult for a new player like BYD to gain a foothold.

Another reason is that there have been concerns about the quality of Chinese-made products, including electric cars. The US government has raised concerns about Chinese companies using stolen technology, and there have also been concerns about the safety of Chinese-made electric cars.

Additionally, there are regulatory barriers that BYD and other Chinese automakers face when trying to enter the US market. For example, they must comply with US safety and emissions regulations, which can be costly and time-consuming.

I am aghast by both the question and the answer, which both show grave ignorance of innovation policy from people who should know better.

- EVs are superior in many ways to ICEs. As a matter of fact, most people who start driving EVs don't want to go back to ICEs because of the vastly superior driving experience.
- From gvt perspective, relying on oil makes you much more vulnerable to short term shocks than relying on renewables. (Yes, renewables create dependence on imports of rare earths etc, but these are long-term challenges that can be managed more easily than short-term oil shocks)
- Besides climate benefits, air quality improvements are worth billions in saved healthcare costs (for both private and public sector) but those are externalities to ICEs and there is no level playing field without government intervention. (this is true - though not as much- even as power is generated from fossil fuels, since the well-to-wheel efficiency of EVs is much more efficient than ICEs)

However, there are significant barriers to EV adoption, that require government intervention.
- First, acquisition costs of EVs are much higher. Though costs have come down significantly over the last years, there is still some way to go, that require (temporarily subsidised) demand so technological learning can do it's thing
- People are used to compare acquisition costs of new cars, where ICEs have an advantage. When doing the proper math of TCO (Total cost of Ownership) which includes energy and maintenance, EVs are a lot more attractive and in many cases more competitive. This requires time and education, and yes, an initial push by government programs.
- Range anxiety is a real thing and needs to be addressed by both manufacturers making more efficient batteries and deployment of public (fast) charging infrastructure. This requires subsidies before network effects take over (enough EVs to justify commercial investments in charging infra and vice-versa)

Another implication is that policymakers should try to unlock the apparent mystery that the more successful European economies pose. Once these myths are jettisoned, policymakers will be liberated to ask: Why have these countries been able to combine high levels of economic performance and productivity with high levels of equality? What economic and social policies have enabled them to achieve this? Why do their citizens appear willing to accept the high rates of taxation that are necessary to finance their generous social provisions?

Nevertheless, there are some reasons for concern. To begin with, the state may have become less redistributive at a time when its redistribution functions are needed most. Government policies over the decade may have accentuated the rising income inequality wrought by market forces. For instance, the tax system has become less progressive. Corporate and personal income taxes have been reduced significantly while the Goods and Services Tax (GST), which is a regressive tax, has been more than doubled. More liberal foreign worker policies might also have worsened income inequality in Singapore.

What about Singapore’s experience? Has trickle-down worked? It is less clear whether the increase in income inequality in Singapore over the last decade has been accompanied by a similarly perverse distribution of income to the super-rich as experienced in the US.

Income inequality in Singapore has risen significantly in the last decade. 
Whether measured by the Gini coefficient, or by the ratio of incomes between the top and bottom quintiles, the evidence points to an incontrovertible fact: Singapore has become a lot more unequal in the last ten years or so. While the fact of increased inequality is beyond dispute, there is little agreement in government that it represents a problem that merits serious policy action.

Worth noting when governments illegal tax by default *they have to give it back*. BUT what usually happens is legislation is passed to make it retrospectively legal. Eg, the federal government could pass legislation to make itself the body that was owed the revenue rather than the states. Collect the revenue, then give it back to the states. This is how they've dealt with taxes that were provisionally collected and the enabling legislation never passed. They just pass legislation that makes the historical collection legal but not future collection. That was how they dealt with some of the changes to alcohol taxes that went into effect but never actually passed, though in that case it was utterly impractical to return the tax to everyone that bought a drink individually :o

It didn't make sense to put a charge in now. But arguing on the basis that the excise went into consolidated revenue is asinine. Everything goes into consolidated revenue. Even the very few things (usually at local level) that are flagged to be spent on a specific thing, actually go into consolidated revenue and are then equal spending comes from it. Fuel excise is in effect the same as a per km road user tax but one that applies a higher amount to less efficient vehicles. It makes ZERO sense to apply a road user tax to petrol/diesel vehicles as well, as moving the tax to that instead of excuse would reduce the incentive for electrification or higher efficiency. Pretending there could be both is in denial of reality, since no politician that suggested a new tax on all cars would survive until lunchtime. Eventually, there will be a road user tax on EVs, and eventually, it will have to replace all of the excise currently collected. 

Regardless of where the money goes, a loss in revenue for taxes somewhere needs to be replaced or spending cut. When we have one of the lowest uptakes of EVs is not the time, but there will be a time, likely when most new car sales are EVs, though well before the whole fleet is EVs.

You, like all the other supporters of EVs I ve seen, heard about and read about, are still ignoring the giant woolly mammoth in the room.  Even if the charging networks provide all the chargers for free, who is going to pay for two other things which are *ALSO* essential - the increase in power required from our power stations, AND the uprating of the national grid to handle the vast increase in current consumption required, even if they only have to cover 20 million cars and trucks?
All very well a charging company providing a super fast charger at zero cost;  but do you think you can plug that into a 13 Amp socket?
More output from power stations is a big enough problem;  at least power stations are normally built as close to main population centres, so if the 132,000 Volt lines have to be enlarged or doubled up, they'll be pretty short.  But all that current has to be then stepped down by local sub-stations fitted with massive transformers.  You want more current going into a certain area?  Then you need more or larger transformers - and bear in mind, they're big enough that you need a *crane* to lift those transformers off the trucks that deliver them, so they aren't cheap.
Get power from windmills?  Sure - then the cabling problem gets even worse, because the windmills are not close to population centres, they're out in the middle of nowhere (or even out in the bloody North Sea!).
And who do think is going to pay for all the extra fitters you need to hire, as well as pay for the cable, sub-stations, power stations, and however many THOUSAND skilled fitters you need to upgrade the power networks in time for this supposed "no IC vehicles sold after 2035"?
You want more?  NO problem.
Over 40% of all homes in Britain have NO secure off-road parking. If they aren't fortunate enough to have car parks provided by their employers WITH charging points, how and where are they suposed to get their EVs charged?
And a final shot across your bows;  the biggest supermarket in my nearest town has parking spaces for 235 cars.  Just TWO of them are equipped to charge EVs, and I've never seen any instance of 'charging point rage'.  Conclusion?  Most people round here don't buy an EV unless (1) they only do short journeys, AND (2) they have a charging point at home.

I enjoyed your research, but I fear, you have missed some key points.

OK, BEVs are notorious for their lack of range and extended charge times (in comparison to petrol/diesel). An ICE, can be refuelled in just 5 minutes, whereas, the best time using a fast charge circuit is around 20 mins. That of course produces queues. Of course, the simple answer is more fast chargers.

But, this is where your investigation alas fails. As an example, assuming  a 150kw charger, it would require a 300 amp 3 phase circuit. That is a hefty cable, then multiply it by the number of chargers on a site. The mains supply circuit, is going to be massive, in your presentation you also conceived the idea of a 300kw charger.

You mention the "grid", not sure whether you mean the national grid, or the renewable grid i.e. wind turbines.

I'll assume you mean the latter. In which case, my response to that is, it will never happen. The hype at the moment is all about "green" renewable energy, particularly wind.

What you are not being told, is just how mammoth a task, that is. Since this government, and future governments, are legally tied to "net-zero", the plan is not realistic, either financially or infrastructure.

To replace our current power stations, will require the building of some 130,000 turbines, occupying about 13,000 sq miles of land, but that is just to replace our current electrical supply. If you then want to include transport, and of course transition to heat pumps. Then the network will have to be three times as large. Curiously, about 1/3rd would be to replace electric supply, another 1/3rd to replace gas (heating), and a final 1/3rd to convert transport to electric.

The cost of doing that will be in excess of £3Tn, that cost is not just for the wind farms, but a complete overhaul and reengineering of the national grid, which carries the power.

Apart from the phenomenal unaffordable cost, consider also, the sourcing of raw materials, to build the new infrastructure, the truth is that the materials would just not be available. Then add to that the maintenance, and the limited 20-year lifespan of the turbines.

You mention, that there was a company, that was willing to install the charging systems for free, well recall the  saying "there's no such thing as a free lunch". Somebody, somewhere ends up paying, and that would be in the charges for the electricity.

Hopefully, other readers of this posting, who may be very pro BEVs, may give this posting some serious consideration. If you still have doubts, please give some time to watching this post on the Tom Nelson channel, in an interview with Prof Michael Kelly, professor of Electrical & Electronic Engineering Cambridge Uni. He's done research into the entire concept.

When I visited in Sweden a few days ago one petrol station had a "temporary" charger. It's a movable unit with battery storage and 4 Kempower dispensers capable to share out 300kW of power load balanced. The 300kWh battery storage means it only needs at a minimum a 43kW grid connection. All packaged in a unit that is the same size as a 20feet container which means regulatory it is much easier to get approval to put down a "temporary" structure which is basically a container in your car park and hook up a relatively small grid connection to it. Not sure if the approval process is as easy in the UK for "temporary" chargers. As long as you have the right to use the land they can sit there for basically as long as you want to, its a container after all, but they can also be removed in a matter of hours and transported somewhere else should you wish. So current sites that has a measly 50kW charger now can very easily be upgraded to 4 HPCs without needing any larger grid connection. I hope this comes to the UK soon as we really need more HPCs everywhere.

As an Electrician who is (reluctantly) required to deal with our DNO, electrical infrastructure is that main issue here, under investment and poor future planning going back years (probably since they were privatised) is and has been woefully poor.
You cannot just add in 50Kw chargers willy nilly without the capacity to power them any more than you can keep plugging appliances into your house, in the latter example the fuse will blow, there are no fuses on the network so cables will just overload, it is the DNO's responsibility to insure this does not happen. Add to that the additional loads of heat pumps, home chargers and even PV and wind turbines all using those same (old) cables to transmit power in all directions we are now heading towards a critical point of infrastructure meltdown.

We are in the early days of our so call transition away from fossil fuels and already there are major issues with out electrical grid network, it is this that desperately needs to be addressed as we all know how long and expensive these problems take to be dealt with.

Totally agree with the red tape issue but you're ignoring the fundamental issue of where does the electricity come from for all these chargers? Don't say wind, don't say solar. They are only one part of the solution. The grid!.The distribution infrastructure. Are you an professional (that's to say at least degree qualified) electrical engineer? 50kW chargers old hat so just simply swap them out for 300 kW units! Do you really think the supply cables can simply accept 6 times the power draw? Do you recognise that to move to all electric vehicles would require us to double the total generating capacity we have now? And a doubling of the distribution network. Going electric for transport is one small part of addressing the need to limit (not eradicate) CO2 emissions and the problem is too much emphasis is placed on an undeliverable objective at the expense of failing to recognise other equally significant ones.

One thought I have had is whether a start would be to demand that all Local Authorities produce a statement by, say,  the end of 2024 indicating how many charging points they will require in their area within the next 5 years and 10 years? They should be able to estimate the number of vehicles based in their area, entering their area each day and what that will mean for charging capacity requirements. They will also be able to anticipate how many residents will have the ability to charge directly at home and how many live in less suitable properties . Local authorities like North Yorkshire or North Norfolk would also be encouraged to think about the impact on their economy if touring holidays were no longer possible as a result of lack of charging facilities.
Whilst such statements wouldn't address the core issue they would give a nation wide perspective on the extent of the problem and might lead to Government realising that action needs to be taken to achieve the capacity indicated by the statements. I realise that there are already statements of the " we need 300,000 chargers by 2030 " but these are so general as to be meaningless. The biggest barriers in just my opinion are listed below 

1. Price of Ev,s 
Most ev will cots you a min of £10,000 more than there petrol versions & in some cases even as much as £30,000 more , then add in the extra interest  you pay on just that extra cost & most people will be paying at least £15,000 more just to drive an Ev. 

NOTE Ev.s at the moment are losing there value on par or just a little worst than petrol cars 

2. Price of electricity 
As we all know electric has sky rocketed , Yes you can get cheap night rate charging for 4 or 6 hours but you then have to pay more for your electric during the other 18 to 20 hours of that day. Plus something most people don't realise is that you lose so many kw during the transfer & charge process eg lets say you have a 100 kw usable battery & it was on 0% ,  if you put in 100kw of electric it would only take that battery to around 85% charge & the rest would be lost in the transfer / charge process but you will pay for the whole 100 kw , same when you rapid charge. 

NOTE You can still save money owning an Ev if its a company car or you get free charging from somewhere. But unless you do around 15,000 a year & you can charge it for free , you will never recoupe just the extra you paid in interest on the finance / pcp. 

3. Cost overall 
    a. Dealers charging for a yearly service , when it isn't needed & voiding your Warrenty if you don't have it serviced / inspected

On the "something like Ofcom" point it looks like (I didn't know until I Googled it but maybe everyone else here already knows this) there *is* a Government body called the Office for Zero Emission Vehicles (OZEV). On their website it says one of their responsibilities is "supporting charging infrastructure on the wider roads network" (in addition to grants for home and workplace charge points).
It's not clear that they have the same regulatory teeth as Ofcom but they do seem to be the same sort of Government so maybe they could acquire teeth in that respect. 
Another thing I found when Googling is that on 30 March this year (ie just over 2 weeks ago) the Government announced £380 million (or £381 million, depending which press release you read...) to launch something called the "Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure fund" (LEVI Fund) which is supposedly about helping "local authorities in England to work with the chargepoint industry" which would seem to be *exactly* the sort of thing discussed in this video. The Energy Saving Trust seem to be closely involved in this.
Will it work? I'm no expert in these things so I don't know; I'm sure many others here will be better informed.
But is it a good time to engage with this new LEVI fund that's just been set up, maybe by engaging with your local authority or the Energy Saving Trust...? I'd suggest it might be an opportunity, for folks living in England at least.

‘A dog’s breakfast’ about sums it up. As you say, there are a whole host of issues compounding these delays. Having spoken to electricians and power distribution network operators about the state of our low voltage distribution network, it is clear that decades of under investment are a significant barrier, not just to the rollout of EV charging infrastructure, but also to domestic and community renewable energy. The investment track record of our electricity network operators in the U.K. is DIRE. When Western Power was bought out by National Grid in our area, I was naive enough to believe there might finally be some investment in our flaky distribution network - we’ve had to put up with routine power outages and unstable voltages for more than a decade. No such luck. Like all the other network operators, National Grid is owned by foreign investors with no effective incentives to improve the power supply, and apparently, as with the Water industry, there are no effective penalties to hold them to account. Roll on 2024. A new government is our best hope.

Depending on the grid network in the area this could involve bigger LV or more likely  HV cables in the area. It could involve new substations or possibly new primary substations (the bigger ones). These are not just available off the shelf and are built to order. Larger substations can have a wait of years from order to delivery. 

Then you need permits from the council and dig teams to put in a base and lay cables. Before this legals need to happen to either buy land for the substation or get easements over or under it.

Getting the substation to site may take specialist transport and/or cranes to  get them in place.

Teams need to be arranged to connect all the cables into the substation.

A wait of years can be quite fast working.

They need to put a limit on the time it takes to process things. Figure out what are the bottlenecks and make sure people have that lined up before the process even starts. That way you won’t end up with half built crap deteriorating because some final piece of paper wasn’t properly filled out.

You made a good point regarding the existing ICE infrastructure. I am sure that if we looked at how many petrol stations were in existence at the turn of the last century I am sure it would be a similar scenario to the current EV situation. We need an input from central government to push this along if we are to stand any chance of being ready for the deadline. The appointment of an "Electrification Tsar" with the power to fine councils, networks etc who are dragging their feet will significantly change the situation. I am sure one of the biggest sticking points for people switching to EVs is the parlous state of the charging network.

The legislation banning ICE sales is now almost irrelevant. The market has decided and EV sales are increasing exponentially while ICE decrease exponentially. We’ll be at about 80% EV sales by 2028. Effectively the ICE car will be dying and wriggling in agony on the floor. 

EVs are disruptive technology and as demand for petrol and diesel declines petrol stations will close. They operate on very small margins so a drop in trade can easily make them unviable. 

When we reach this point there will be a big demand for good charging infrastructure. EV drivers will be a significant proportion of drivers, and voters. Government will have a choice of getting things done and supporting the charging infrastructure or subsidising petrol stations for the dying ICE drivers. Let’s hope they make the correct decision.

The DNOs (in my case SSEN, part of SSE plc) clearly just don’t have the capacity to take some of these additions into their network. Often this is because their network requires upgrades to a substation somewhere to provide that additional capacity. It seems to be the same on the generation side, with limitations on how much PV can be fed back to the grid. 

Unless the charge point installers and charging network operators are prepared to put their hand in their pocket to cover more of the upgrades needed to the network to provide that capacity, the commissioning of new sites will just drag on until the network gets upgraded anyway. 

This does need an Ofgem type of body to either assist the DNOs in adding capacity to the electricity network or finding better ways to coordinate and balance the grids in a given area.

Let me bust the lies in this video and generally being circulated and truths being censored by Tata Motors:

About me: I own Tata Nexon EV max lux XZ, I purchased it on 3rd of Feb 2023.

1. The talked range of 330 by owner ( which more of a looks like Tata Sales person) you will never achieve that. Maximum practical range that you should expect is around 250kms.

2. This car is too congested at the back seat, there is not even space for 2 people to sit comfortably let aside 3 people. Leg space is too little, battery position pushes the entire floor of the car a little more upwards, which further reduces the leg space.

3. This car lacks a state of art finishing, looks like more of a jugaad, you can see wires coming out of different places beneath the seat, near by to brakes,under the car. Also looking the car from outside doesn’t look like a industry grade finishing.

3. Subsidy that you get is totally arbitrary, from my personal experience it’s been more than 2.5 months for me, still have not received the subsidy. It is pending with Egrasy’s account officer for more than 2  months.

4. There is no myth of sunroof being small, it’s truth it’s placed at the very wrong position, neither the person sitting at the back or at front seat can easily manage to go out.

5. Never ever plan to take this car out, I went to Rishikesh there is no charging infra there, it takes at least 2 hours to fully charge it with fastest charger available in the market (as Tata throttles charging at 30KW/H doesn’t matter what is the chargers capacity.  Also, all fast charger providers are charging per unit @20-23rs/unit + 10% GST.

6. Slow chargers (3 and 7kw/H) will take around 13 and 6 hours to charge it fully, forget using these chargers when you are on a trip. Also, I live in a society where there is no charging infra, no support from societies for chargers installation my Society is asking for a deposit of 50k to enhance the load and will charge per unit at a commercial rate of 14rs/KW.

7. Tata support and service is worst, it took me 5 days to get a pick up schedule for my first service, and after that they delivered the car without wash. It needed me to raise this issue with Sheel(Tata Motors India Sales head) to solve this petty issue. 

Personally I am looking to sell this car and go with a hybrid one.

The shortage of natural gas supply from Russia could cause a collapse of industry in Germany.. 

Germany is heavily reliant on natural gas from Russia, which accounts for 35% of its imports of the fuel.
Natural gas is a vital energy source for Germany, which accounts for about a quarter of the country’s total energy mix.
Russia has already cut gas flows to Germany by 60% since June 2021, citing an equipment hold-up in Canada as a result of sanctions over the war in Ukraine.
Germany fears that the situation may get worse after the scheduled shutdown of the Nord Stream 1 pipeline for maintenance from July 11 to July 212. There is no guarantee that the gas flows will resume after that.
Entire industries in Germany, such as aluminum, glass, and chemical industry, are in danger of collapsing permanently because of the gas bottlenecks. These industries employ hundreds of thousands of people and contribute significantly to the country’s economy.
The gas shortage is also driving inflation to record highs, which threatens social stability and consumer spending.
Germany has moved into the second stage of its three-stage emergency gas plan, which involves securing alternative supplies and energy sources, easing infrastructure bottlenecks, encouraging energy savings, and expanding solidarity agreements to share gas across countries1. However, these measures may not be enough to cope with a total shutoff of Russian gas.
A total shutoff of Russian gas could lead to shortages of 15% to 40% of annual consumption in some countries in Central and Eastern Europe, which are also dependent on Russian gas. This could have spillover effects on Germany’s trade, investment, and financial links with these countries.
A total shutoff of Russian gas could also reduce Germany’s gross domestic product by up to 6%, according to some estimates3. This would be a severe setback for the country’s economic recovery from the pandemic.

Another imminent issue is electricity grid capacity.  I live in the UK and for the second winter running, the government have introduced (a quite feeble) incentive for consumers to cut back on their domestic electricity consumption at peak times.  They do this with a series of target periods, trying to fool us by making it sound like a game to win prizes.  Today we are all being asked to cut back between 5:30PM and 6:30PM.

Of course they blame Ukraine, Gaza, unicorn infestations, everything but the honest truth.

Firstly, it is winter, it is getting colder, electricity consumption increases - nothing is going to change that.

But the two unspokens are immigration and EV charging.  

This year the nett migration into the UK increased the population by 1%.  That means without doing anything, the electricity grid needs to supply an additional 1% of energy.  And that is going to increase at that rate year on year until something breaks.

And there are more EVs about, not as many as the government would like, but definitely more.  My household is a heavier than average electricity consumer.  Heating and hot water is gas-powered, which is pretty common in the UK, although the crazy government wants to end that too.  But I mostly work from home, so in all day, I work in IT so am running at least three computers all the time, I use the large screen TV a lot, my son and my wife have computers too, and cooking is all electric. And that amounts to about 70kWh per week.  Now to fully charge a typical EV from empty also takes about 70kWh.  So charging an EV just once per week is the equivalent to the needs of an above-average house.  Estimates say that there are 28 million houses and 1 million EVs in the UK.  So just charging each EV once per week is equivalent to a 3.6% increase in the number of households demanding electricity.

At the moment it is just non-compulsory games, but you can see where it is going, it is clear that there are very real concerns that the electricity grid cannot handle peak loads - today it is non-compulsory games, tomorrow it is likely to be mandatory rationing.

You are a two car family and you have to charge both cars each night at home for work the following day. Your house was built in the 60s and the electric cables feeding your house from the grid were sized to meet the demand and maybe a bit more on the day the house was built. Copper is expensive so the engineers will have taken care to calculate the size of cable required. Since the house was built many things have changed including the number of electrical appliances being run in your house. You now have microwaves air fryers computers lots of TVs all these things will have taken up any spare capacity in your cables. Now you want to add the load of two car chargers to the house. The bad news is the cables are not big enough to carry the current they need and you are risking a fire from overloading the mains. Now think about the cables feeding your house and your neighbours they too want to charge their cars and their cables will have been sized for the expected load when they were built. Now the whole street is overloading the cables. To make it work you would need to replace all the cables feeding older properties install more generation power and transformers to carry the extra power.

Did they remove the Non-Refundable Credit provisions in the latest bill?  My understanding was that the Qualified Plug-in Electric Drive Motor Vehicle Credit is a non refundable credit. 

A non refundable credit can reduce your tax liability to 0 (zero), however it cannot result in a refund. What this means is if you qualify for a $350 credit and your tax liability is $200, you will only receive a $200 credit on your return. If your tax liability is zero you would not receive the credit at all, even though you are otherwise eligible for it.

As of 10 Jun 2023, the electric vehicle tax credit is nonrefundable, meaning taxpayers who purchase qualifying electric vehicles or plug-in hybrid vehicles can lower their tax liability by the corresponding credit amount. The credit can make a sizable dent in the tax bill, but it won't result in a refund beyond that.  I would recheck your source.

The Internal Combustion Engine & the Future of the Human Race 
-- An Invention We Cannot Live Without!
(I hope someone from Senator Cornyn's office will read this carefully and pass it along to him. I've been studying this subject since 2005, and I know whereof I speak.) 

The internal combustion engine is one of the most important inventions upon which our entire civilization depends. And, there is no comparison between an internal combustion engine and any electrically powered vehicle. There are numerous things an 'IC-Engine can do which EV's will never be able to do. First and foremost, the driver of an IC-Engine can dramatically increase the power (torque) of the engine simply by foot-pressure on the gas-pedal. Ask any working farmer with an IC Pickup Truck how important that is. Another difference? If you run out of gas in an IC-Engine, all you need is a hand-held auxiliary gas-can you can dump into the vehicle. Imagine having to put a spare-tank of EV batteries in the back of your truck? If you consider the tanks our military uses, there is no way we'll ever be able to make a practical and capable tank based on batteries. The only way to power this enormously heavy vehicles is using an IC-Engine -- up to and including in some cases, actual rocket engines. (Yes Virginia, Rockets are 'internal combustion engines too!).  


That said: we are facing a climate crisis which could decimate human civilization if we continue to convert our fossil fuel deposits into atmospheric CO2. Need I repeat that? If we keep going as we are, it will be catastrophic for human civilization. 

More to the point, the fossil fuels we currently use in or IC-engines are running out. Those fuels took 500-million years to accumulate. Yet, we have burned through (arguably) 50% of our fossil fuels in just 200 years. Think about that!?! How could we continue binging on fossil-fuels and not change the climate!


What is the solution? Its not switching to EVs! The solution is obvious: we need to produce Carbon-Neutral Hi-energy equivalents to Kerosene and Gasoline. And our Oil companies know this! 
Not only do they know it, they're the companies in the best position to establish a new industry producing Carbon-Neutral Liquid Fuels (CNLF), cultivated in the planet's oceans.  

How do you cost-effectively produce CNLF? Thanks to Jimmy Carter, we know how to do it. Carter funded the "Aquatic Species Research Program" in 1978. and over a period of about 10 years, scientists developed prototypes of so-called 'Bio-Reactors' capable of cultivating 'Algal' to produce high-energy liquid fuels on a sustainable basis. The problem with bio-reactors? They were designed to be built in our country's desert SW regions, requiring cost-prohibitive plumbing and maintenance.What's the common-sense solution? Create vast arrays of Deep-Ocean Algal (algae) based cultivation networks in the planet's deep oceans, particularly those with naturally occurring beneficial sea-water nutrients (aka: HNLC zones), such as those off the west-coast of South America. 

Algae happens to be the single largest bio-mass on Earth. Its the foundation of the entire Ocean Food Chain. Algae takes the energy of the sun and CO2 out of the water in which it lives, and converts it into hydrocarbons. Thats exactly how our fossil-fuels were created! Furthermore, by establishing Deep Ocean Aquaculture of this kind, we will be able to reinforce and rebuild our ocean fisheries.

This isn't just a good-idea, its an absolutely essential step that we, as a species, must take in order to establish sustainable and portable energy resources for mankind going forward from the here and now. If we don't do it (and assuming our continued reliance on fossil-fuels), we will render catastrophic damage to our existing biosphere. One need look no further than the annual snow-melt in the Arctic (particularly the thousands of gigatons of fresh water dumped into the Atlantic Ocean by Greenland each year), to recognize the threat that poses to densely populated sea-level zones around the world. Not just Bangladesh, and countries in the vicinity of India, but places like New Orleans, Miami Beach, Chesapeake Bay, and New York City, all of which are already under siege by rising sea-levels (a few inches every year).

Yes, there are already many experimental projects in progress attempting to cultivate algae as a source of sustainable liquid fuels. Unfortunately, in almost every case, the scale of the methodology is insufficient to the task at hand: producing carbon-neutral high-energy liquid fuels at a cost per barrel equal to or less than what we're spending on fossil-liquid-fuels. Not saying its going to be easy to do, but compared to some of the other great things we've accomplished to-date (as a species), I'm suggesting that if we focus on this goal, we can find a way to achieve it. And one more thing? If we don't, the doomsayers who have been flogging the Solar-Panels & Windmills 'solution' may well succeed in sending humankind to an early grave in this century.

If the DOE (Dept of Energy) thinks its a more efficient use of petroleum oil, to burn it in an electrical generation plant, then we have some real idiots working for the DOE.  The process of converting oil & natural gas from feed stock crude into electricity involves an energy conversion loss of 65% of the energy contained within the oil, to operate the turbines that produce the electricity.  That makes electricity production a real energy hog.  And it will only make it more expensive to light, or heat, or cool your house the more that EVs are promoted by this corrupt government.

The EV being pushed by our corrupt government is really just a way of extracting taxpayer funds to make politically connected people wealthy, and the EV purchase subsidy is a BRIBE to promote EV usage and keep the money spigot flowing from taxpayer funds to the corrupt 'Green Energy' faction.  What you will never be told is that EVs waste MORE oil & natural gas than gasoline engines do...  If people were educated, they'd know that electricity to power lighting and heating/air conditioning is about to become way more expensive for the average home, because of the EV demand the corrupt politicians are trying to create.
Its just a means of transferring massive amounts of cash from the slush fund we call the IRS, to politically connected individuals.  The EV concept itself is a fraud... not just because of the huge oil usage in their manufacture, and dirty battery construction, those are a disgusting waste, but people are so dumb that NOBODY seems to know that when an EV is plugged into the power outlet, it's using oil & natural gas that is burned in electrical generation plants.  And that the energy loss (energy conversion loss) that occurs when oil or gas is burned to heat the boilers that then spin the turbines to create the electricity... is a loss of 66% of the energy that's burned, giving you a 34% output of energy in the form of electrical energy, which then goes into the national electrical grid... where an additional 10% of THAT energy (in the form of electricity) is lost from the grid via electron migration, because it just leaks out into the air at a steady rate.  SO, now you have a net loss of the energy from the petroleum inputs totaling 66% plus 10% of the captured electricity (.10X.34=3.5%), for a total loss of 69.5% of the energy that was contained in the oil or natural gas.  Then too, the battery of the EV also leaks electricity via electron migration (especially in cold weather) losing another five percent of the electrical energy.  It means that anyone who is pro-conservation, and wants to see petroleum products used efficiently, cannot justify the EV industry on any level, because making electricity and holding it in a battery wastes so much of the oil energy inputs.  It's a bad joke calling it 'Green'.  But corrupt politicians know the people are dumb, and they can take your tax money.  We call that a scam where I'm from (Boston).  AS far as GASOLINE powered combustion engines go... first, a gallon of gasoline is a distilled fractionate of oil that represents only a portion of each barrel of crude oil, other fractionated petroleum products are produced during the same oil distilling process.  And the energy 'conversion loss' of burning gasoline in a car motor is through heat, as the motor puts out heat from the combustion cycle.  Overall, a typical gasoline engine is a more efficient use of petroleum energy.

The reality of climate change is that it is based entirely on mathematical ‘worse case scenario’ computer models and not in any way shape or form on proven or provable peer reviewed scientific fact.

The most damning confirmation that emphatically proves the climate change lie is that In 1989, we were warned by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change that, according to their worse case scenario computer models, unless we reduced the levels of CO2 in our atmosphere, we would experience global warming on a scale never before seen. 

They further warned that we only had 10 years to save the planet from catastrophe. If we did not heed this warning and act upon it, the ice caps would melt, the oceans would rise and whole islands and coastal towns would disappear under the waves. Temperatures would rise exponentially causing global warming and millions of people would die of thirst and hunger as whole countries would be turned into virtual deserts. 

1999 came and went and none of their ‘worse case scenario’ computer model predictions came true. Not one. It's now been 34 years since that warning and still none of their predictions have come true... Ask Rishi Sunak to explain that!

Can you please elaborate on how the tax credit works for someone who purchased the Tesla through their LLC or business?

Here are some scenarios to hopefully help explain this non-refundable credit.

1. Person A makes 100k a year. The tax LIABILITY is 24% or 24K. Person A contributed 25k to federal taxes throughout the year in form of paycheck tax deductions. Person A will received a refund of 1k (25k contributed - 24k federal tax liability). 
Now let us say person A bough a Tesla Model 3. This will drop person A's tax liability by 7.5k. Person A federal tax liability is now 16.5k. Person A still contributed 25k in from of paycheck tax deduction so his refund at the end of the year is 8.5k.

2. Person B makes 100k a year but is somehow able to write most of the income off. Let us say they can write off 80k of their income. Person B taxable income is now only 20k. The federal tax liability is 12% or 2.4k. The ev tax credit will drop that liability to 0, but person B will not receive the remainder of the tax credit(non-refundable part).

3. Person C is also making 100K a year with a tax liability of 24k. This person for some reason only contributed 22k to federal tax in form of paycheck tax deductions.  Person C now owes 2k in taxes. 
Person C now buys a Tesla Model 3. Person C tax liability reduces by 7.5k, so person C now has a tax liability of only 16.5k. Person C will now get a refund of 5.5k

Hope this helps. This is not advice, but only running some scenarios.

Lokesh i support your channel and i also support EV for its envir9nmental benifits. But being impartial and just for the sake of debate why government is increasing tax can be aruged in few points. Its just a though and i donot support petroleum vehicles. 
1.  2030 MA india le petroleum vehicle ko production ban gRne bhaneko cha so aba vehicle business bhanekai haal ko laagi electric ra bhabisya ma hydrogen hunecha bhane maintenance ra running ma matra petroleum hunch cha. Sangai nepal ko environmental law anusar nepal ma used product lerauna mildaina so following india nepal ma ni 2030 pachi naya gadi petroleu audaina. 

2. Nepali dollar bahira jane hisab ma, ahile 12 lakhs ma petroleum gadi aaucha bhane tesko equivalent EV ko india ma around 35 lacs parcha NRs ma . Yedi 25 barsha ko car ko active life manne ho bhane pani 25 barsha ma baaki (35-12)= 23 lacs ko petrol import gare pachi balla bara bari ma aaucha. So EV le dollar bachauna reduce garcha tara dherai contribute gardaina. 

Having said that i still support EV and hydrogen vehicles and nepal being young country can adapt faster to the technology and it should make policies accordingly.
