Nice video. In my case infortunately, I had booked Ola S1 Air way back on October 2022. I  was planning to wait for 6-7 months as pricings were supposed to go up after 1 June.

But my current scooter Mahindra Rodeo is giving issues every month and breaking down any where on road. I am getting no support for it from Company. Most of the times parts are unavailable. Most mechanics decline to service the Mahindra scooter. So I have to buy a new scooter now.

As such my daily running is not much (4km per day). So comsidered a petrol scooter like Yamaha Fascino for some time. Just because it is said to give a very good fuel efficiency (55-60kmpl in real world. There are also instances where people got 100kmpl+ in standard driving conditions under guidance of showroom/company. Videos are available on YouTube).

But I really want to shift to electric. So I went ahead and booked Ola S1 Air. 

It costed me 1,14,500 in Pune without insurance, without extended guarantee, without Ola Care Plus.

I will have to shell out another 4500₹ for insurance (Acko Insurance) before taking delivery. Its still cheaper by 1000₹ than insurance which Ola is providing (5,500₹, Acko Insurance).

I hope I am taking correct decision by buying Ola S1 Air. Fingers crossed.

Before you install solar panels, you need to assess the structure of your roof. You may have to do some bracing if you won't want the weight of the panels to start making your roof sag over the next several years. That is one reason insurance companies don't like them. If they're not installed correctly, they can damage the structure of the roof. Also, do not--I repeat DO NOT install panels on a roof that may need work in the future since if you have to have the roof redone, the roofing company is not going to take on the liability of removing and re-installing the panels. Not their expertise. You'll have to have that done separately and it will add thousands to the job. If you're going to get solar panels, almost better to use them to cap a newly built gazebo sort of structure in the back yard instead of putting them on the roof of the home itself.

99% of people don't understand how insurance works. I would say at least 80% of Americans are under insured. Items like jewelry, guns and electronics are limited on policies so most only cover about $500 total. Car insurance is the same way. Most Americans don't have enough liability on their insurance policy to cover them in case of an accident. If you take the basic coverage for your state and you have an accident You could be on the hook for thousands of dollars. Question:  Why are insurance companies dropping homeowners with solar panels?
Answer:  It's all about Underwriting risks Vs. rewards (premium received).
Think about it.  An insurance company, like any business can only stay open, if it can make a profit.
How much they charge is based on 'risks' at the time the policy is issued.
If you change (especially, increase) the risk, then the insurer should either collect more premium or reassess whether or not 'the risk' is worth it to them.  Hence, canceling policies.

While solar panels may reduce the electrical bill for the homeowner, it does the opposite for an insurer.
It cost 'this much' to repair or replace a roof after a covered peril (for ex., wind or hurricane), but it'll cost 'that much more' if solar panels were added.

Also, let's not forget that solar panels are not 'magically installed' onto a roof.  Holes need to be drilled into the roof for 'mounting hardware' and therefore, making the roof more susceptible to failure (rain intrusion).  Who has to deal with these claims and payouts?  Insurance companies.

The idea that the panels "protect" your roof (Solar Salesman) is absolutely LAUGHABLE.   From hail, maybe.   (1)  wind during hurricanes passes both over and under the panel, creating "lift" in the same manner of an airplane wing.  All of the fastener points where the panels are attached are now under uplift strain, cause both risk to general roof damage as well as to water leakage.  If the majority or entire roof is covered with panels, it also prohibits firefighters from being able to vent a roof during a fire because they can't cut open the roof....the panels are in the way.  And because the electricity from the panels feeds the electrical system constantly except at night, there is no method to cut the power during a fire.  So firefighters will stay on the outside and spray water in, but won't be inclined to enter the house for life safety reasons.  This is not an anti-solar post...but for heaven's sake, mount the panels on ground level in the yard or along the driveway.   Putting them on rooftops is only recommended by the people trying to sell you the system saying that is where they are unobstructed and most efficient.   But if you put them on your rooftop, expect those who are taking the financial risk on that rooftop to say "sorry  -  pass".

Solar panels in Florida provide virtually zero protection against hurricane-induced power outages.  Thanks to some trickery by the various Florida power companies when they'd floated our constitutional amendment regarding solar panels, all home solar systems in Florida MUST be connected to the power grid, MAY NOT have any energy storage capabilities (such as batteries) and therefore may only put the captured solar energy into the power grid, and MUST be powered down in the event of a power outage.  If a hurricane takes out the power grid, Florida law *prohibits* solar system owners from using their solar power systems!  

I'd damned near pulled my hair out while trying to get my fellow Floridians to actually read the proposed amendment, titled along the lines of "Protecting Solar Power for Homeowners Amendment" or some such garbage, instead of just listening to the title and thinking "my, how nice and friendly!", but nope.  The amendment wasn't very long, but taking the five minutes (literally) to read it was too much to ask of our citizens, so we are stuck with being told by the fossil-fuel power-plant operators when we may use our own, privately owned power generating solar panels.

Oh, and the payment from the power companies back to the homeowners for the power that is contributed to the grid are most likely to essentially evaporate.  The result will be, essentially, that the homeowner will pay for their own equipment but will be paid back for the energy at a rate of about half of what is paid to those commercial power companies when they sell to the local power company.  In other words, the solar-panel owning homeowner must pay for the equipment and then subsidize the power company that they are required to supply.  In other words, Floridians who install home-wide solar panel systems will have to pay MORE for their energy than those who simply purchase it from the power company.

Gee, it almost seems as if the power companies in Florida actually want to dissuade homeowners from installing and using solar panels.

EV technology simply isn't advanced enough to take over as fuel and hybrid vehicles.  The grid itself couldn't handle the increased load, and outside the urban areas and local commutes, they can't fulfill those needs.  Outside the EU, Japan and China, public mass transit isn't even viable in the near future, unless a drastic overhaul and investment is made.

Even streamlining a national fast rail project would provide some substantial improvements toward moving away from the reliance on gas/diesel markets. You are  going to need a proportional scaled Grid & Transmission system, right from Generation through to Distribution..to match this consumption... Separate and ON TOP of the Grid and Transmission system that you already have that currently supplies Energy to your Industrial/Commercial and Residential consumers and customers. Ok lets look at the boring stuff for a moment. Outside of  a specific Commercial Charging station... of which this still applies on another scale... lets look at a street or cul-de-sac of 10 homes for application of domestic charging of EVs. (remember they already have an existing house supply burden).. so a specific metered pilot system would need to be installed, for each domestic charging setup. ANOTHER Transformer,  will also need to be installed, that will need to have  3 phases HV and LV supplies balanced for Distribution purposes. So you can now expand this small 10 house example, to the very real 100s and 1000s of houses that the astronomical installation Costs this would apply, to see how unrealistic that just EVs ALONE are going to be the whole future of vehicle travel. How Human Nature Works
Human nature is the desire to receive, also called “desire to enjoy,” and it functions by receiving what is beneficial to itself and rejecting what is harmful. Everything in our lives is built upon this calculation where we first try to distance ourselves from harm, and then seek how to draw ourselves closer to what is beneficial.
Human nature also includes a multilayering of systems that work simultaneously on still, vegetative, animate and human levels. One of those systems is our bodily one, which operates involuntarily. If our bodies are healthy, then they know what is good for them and draw that goodness to themselves. After the bodily system, there is the emotional system, which also functions relatively according to instinct. From the emotional system, we move to the mind, and from the mind to the intellect, and so on. That is, we have systems over systems that concurrently work on receiving what is beneficial and rejecting what is harmful.
Such is human nature and the essence of our lives. Our every desire, thought and action operates according to the calculation, “How can we receive what is most beneficial to us and reject what is harmful?”

The government is not against people using good or luxury cars;
 however, they prioritize the manufacturing of these cars within India. By imposing import duties on cars, the government provides car companies to manufacture vehicles domestically.

When we purchase a foreign car for 20 rupees, the Indian government receives 10 rupees, and the Reserve Bank of India needs to provide a dollar equivalent of 10 rupees to the exporting company. This scenario is considered unfavorable for the Indian economy.

On the other hand, if we buy a similar quality car manufactured in India for 15 rupees, the government receives the entire 15 rupees. (Win-win for everyone) This is because none of the money spent on the car leaves India, and it circulates within the domestic economy, ultimately contributing to government revenue through recursive tax.

It's important to clarify that the Society of Indian Automobile Manufacturers (SIAM) is not lobbying for these measures. Instead, this taxation system is a common practice employed by countries worldwide, particularly in the case of large nations like India.

While I don't want to belittle ASML produces the most advanced photolithography equipment today, I must clarify ASML cannot excel without the 5000 suppliers beneath it!   Many of them have the commanding position in their respective fields too.   For example, the mirrors in the ASML machine are made by Germany's Zeiss and state of the art.   Said differently, ASML's equipment is NOT one technology but an ECOSYSTEM of many different disciplines.   Therefore, even if China can replicate ASML as a system integrator, its ability to produce finish goods still hinges on the 5000 suppliers being allowed to export to China!   Can China become number one in 5000 different fields and become totally independent?   Further, buying equipment and how you use it are two different subjects!   I can buy the same oven used by a world famous chef, but I can't bake award-winning cookies because that chef has his secret recipes but I follow the cookbook that comes with the oven.   NO semiconductor manufacturing companies follow the recipes that come with the equipment!   This is why though Intel can buy the same equipment from ASML like TSMC, Intel is no match for TSMC.  The latter has developed  much more advanced recipes that are years ahead.   In summary, no one single company can control the semiconductor "industry" (more of an ecosystem of thousands of different technologies).   The true advantage of the U.S. is that all leading players are in North America, Western Europe, Japan, South Korea and Taiwan, and none of them dare to play hardball against Washington!

Yes, current borders do cause military confrontations. But, I think you are actually missing the true root causes of the ongoing conflicts in the region. A very compelling alternative to this can be found in the book "The Long Great War" by Jonathan Wyrtzen. The accepted narrative for regional conflict that blames colonially imposed borders misses the fact that the region has many local groups vying for control, as well as deep underlying cultural acceptance of conflict as the primary means of dealing with disagreements. In other words, assuming that if colonial powers had not drawn these borders, the region would have ascended into some utopian peace is not based on any historical precedence. This leads to regional leaders blaming others for ongoing conflict instead of taking responsibility for it themselves. In short, this continued narrative is partly to blame for the ongoing conflict, and should be reconsidered.

The irony is that the British opposed development of the canal, would not invest in its construction and considered it would threaten the monopoly of their naval trading supremacy. The British acquired a controlling share in the Suez Canal after the financial crisis of the Khedive of Egypt, Ismail Pasha. In the mid-1870s, Ismail Pasha had incurred massive debts due to his modernisation efforts in Egypt. To alleviate this financial crisis, he offered his country’s shares in the Suez Canal for sale.

In November 1875, British Prime Minister Benjamin Disraeli seized this opportunity and bought Egypt’s shareholding for £4 million. This purchase established Britain’s influence in the running of this new and extremely important waterway. The acquisition of these shares allowed Britain to assume control of the surrounding region, including Egypt and the Sudan.

Insurance companies will not cover rental car companies for free as they would go broke. Your personal auto insurance policy will cover a rental vehicle for damage only when your personal vehicle is in the shop for service or body shop. You do not need the collision damage waiver from the rental car company as your credit card company will cover any loss as per your credit card agreement. I would recommend that you contact your credit card company with any questions before you rent a vehicle. Chase Sapphire is using the term primary for marketing purposes for travel related rentals. The other credit card companies using the term secondary does not matter as the insurance companies will not cover rental vehicles for travel or personal use.

Great job with lots of helpful info!  However, to say that secondary insurance coverage, which is provided by some credit cards, is useless in not true.  Some people may not have collision and comprehensive coverage on their own auto policy, in which case the credit card insurance will pay.  Also, even if you have collision and comprehensive on your own car, it will only pay up to the current value of your own car.  If the rental car is worth more than your own car, than the damage you cause to the rental car may be more than the limit on your personal car insurance, in which case the credit card insurance will pay the difference.

Overall love your work, however this one missed the mark for me a bit.  For (2) of your 'hacks', you left off the key part of the information, the 'why' for the hack that explains why it will work because that helps people to understand changes they can make without just being random.  

First, the 1 hr difference.  The key to know is that almost all rental car companies rent on the 24 hour day.  So, this hack is only going to work if your removed hour is going from 25 hours to 24 hours.  A 'sub-hack' for this is to know that most rental car companies work in terms of 'real' time.  If you made the reservation for 9am and end up picking up the car at 9:15am, your reservation doesn't start until 9:15am and you don't have to return it until 9:15am the next day.  Also most give you a bit of a buffer.  In this same situation, most will let you return the car at 9:45am without extra charges....But, be sure to read the fine print. 


Second, the 5 to 7 days price decrease.  Since you didn't mention it, I doubt people realize the reason for the major difference is because of the WEEKLY vs DAILY rate.  Most rental agencies give you a much better rate for a weekly rental versus individual days, meaning there is often a break-even point in the 4-6 day range at which point, the week becomes cheaper.  Great idea, but you missed the opportunity to explain why the hack worked.
